speculum-0258.value: Although the quadrifrons arch or ianus (passageway) represented in this print was long believed to have been a temple of the god Janus, there is no clear evidence that it was dedicated to that god. It may have been a monumental reconstruction of the Ianus Primus. See Richardson, pg 208, s.v. Ianus Quadrifrons (1).

speculum-0259.label: Description
speculum-0259.value: Although the text at the bottom of the print identifies this structure as the "sepulchre" of Septimius Severus, this was not its original function. Most likely, it was a monumental facade to the Palatine Hill in the architectural mold of a scenae frons. It has been proposed also that is may have bean a monumental nymphaeum, or fountain, but no traces of waterworks remain in the area so this was probably not the case. For further information, see Richardson, pg. 350, s.v. Septizodium. The Septizodium was destroyed in the 16th century by Pope Sixtus V in order to repurpose the marble. Knowledge of the inscription comes from its having been recorded in epigraphic sylloges and prints such as this one.

speculum-0902.label: Description
speculum-0902.value: This engraving is a duplicate of C 901; it lacks, however, the various legends and the Orsini arms (cf. Ashby, p.129, note 1 and Lowry, col.50b and note 29). The inscription of this statue in the Cavalieri editions, including the 1623 Marcucci one, locates it in front of the house of Cardinal Alfonso Caraffa (1540-1567), who was made a Cardinal on March 15, 1557 (cf. EC v.3, col.98a). In the inscription of the della Vaccheria-van Schayck editions, this house had passed into the hands of a Cardinal of the Sermonetta branch which could mean any of the following members of the Caetani family who in hereditary succession were created Cardinals: Nicolo in 1538; Enrico in 1589; Bonfacio II in 1606; Antonio II in 1621; and Luigi (d.1642), the last Cardinal of that family, in 1626 (cf. EI v.8, p.252). The engraving of this statue executed by Jacques Granthomme ca.1597 is without an inscription but bears on the pedestal what appears to be the Caraffa arms.
